Reaction times

Here is a summary of the RT variable:

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     928    1533    1666    1759    1850    7215

Now let’s see how the RT distribution behave as a function or the load and emotions conditions:

At first sight, RT distribution is likely to fit a gamma distribution.

7 observations could be removed from analysis if we choose to consider them as outliers.
These observations (data from 4 different participants) are listed below.

##   Condition  Response   RT MultiRep Subject Load   Emotion  Side Response_binom
## 1    LW_H_R Incorrect 5216        1     PP4  Low Happiness Right              0
## 2    HW_A_L       Hit 6266        1     PP4 High     Anger  Left              1
## 3    HW_N_R       Hit 5033        1     PP4 High   Neutral Right              1
## 4    LW_H_L       Hit 5832        1    PP12  Low Happiness  Left              1
## 5    HW_H_R       Hit 5015        1    PP13 High Happiness Right              1
## 6    HW_A_L       Hit 5666        1    PP13 High     Anger  Left              1
## 7    HW_H_L       Hit 7215        1    PP18 High Happiness  Left              1

The median RT distribution is quite acceptable and there is no outliers.
This suggests that we do not need to remove the aforementioned 7 RT > 5000 ms.

Modelization and statistics

Accuracy

Modelization

Because participants had two possible type of responses (i.e., Hit and Incorrect), the errors distribution is binomial.
Binomial Generalized Linear Mixed Models, or binomial GLMMs, are useful for modeling binary outcomes for repeated or clustered measures.
Here, we assume that the relationship between the mean of the response and explanatory variables is linear on the logit scale.

The model is build using raw accuracy measurements (coded as “1” for Hit, and “0” for Incorrect), with 2 fixed factor (LOAD and EMOTION) and 1 random factor (SUBJECT; i.e., random intercept by subject for regression).

It is always complex to assess the goodness of fit for binomial models, but here is the distribution of residuals, which seems quite good for a binomial GLMM.

Statistics

The type II Wald test indicate that there is a main effect of the LOAD on accuracy.
There is no effect of the EMOTION factor on accuracy.

Accuracy as a function of the load. Within each boxplot (Tukey method), the horizontal line represents the mean, the box delineates the area between the first and third quartiles (interquartile range); the vertical line represents the interval between quantile 5 and 90 (i.e., the dispersion of 90% of the population); juxtaposed to each boxplot, the dots represent individual performance.

RT

Modelization

The models are build using raw RT, with 2 fixed factor (LOAD and EMOTION) and 1 random factor (SUBJECT; i.e., random intercept by subject for regression).

Here, we fitted the RT distribution with both gaussian and gamma distributions, with a log link or not, and compared these 4 models. There is no significant big difference between these 4 models. The AIC and BIC criterion are lower for the model.3 (model with a simple gamma distribution), but there were convergence warnings for models with gamma distribution (“Model failed to converge with max|grad”, not solved using different kind of optimizers).

## Data: AllData
## Models:
## model.rt.01: RT ~ Load * Emotion + (1 | Subject)
## model.rt.02: RT ~ Load * Emotion + (1 | Subject)
## model.rt.03: RT ~ Load * Emotion + (1 | Subject)
## model.rt.04: RT ~ Load * Emotion + (1 | Subject)
##             npar    AIC    BIC logLik deviance  Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)
## model.rt.01    8 148535 148593 -74260   148519                     
## model.rt.02    8 148663 148721 -74323   148647    0.0  0           
## model.rt.03    8 144346 144404 -72165   144330 4316.7  0           
## model.rt.04    8 144361 144419 -72172   144345    0.0  0

Here, a solution is then to only compare the models fitted with a Gaussian distribution. The first model (without log link) seems better than the second one based on the AIC and BIC criterion. The first model will then be kept for running variance analysis.
